modules.description: Writes 16, 32, 48, and 64-bit unsigned integers, as well as 32 and 64-bit floating-point numbers, into a buffer using big-endian byte order. Operates on an opaque serializer type and integer or float values. Used to construct binary data streams for network protocols or file formats requiring specific byte ordering.

Writes 16, 32, 48, and 64-bit unsigned integers, as well as 32 and 64-bit floats, into a buffer using little-endian byte order. Operates on integer and float values of varying bit widths. Used to serialize numerical data for network transmission or file storage in systems requiring byte-level control.

Provides functions to handle flush and drain events on a stream, tracking the state of output transmission. Works with a custom type representing the stream's status, capturing whether it's been successfully flushed or drained. Used to signal completion or interruption during data transmission in network or I/O operations.

Provides low-level operations for constructing and manipulating byte buffers, with support for efficient memory management during serialization. Works with byte arrays and custom data structures to enable direct control over data output. Used to implement high-performance network protocols and format-specific serializers like JSON.

Encapsulates low-level serialization primitives for writing numeric and floating-point values in both big-endian and little-endian formats, along with mechanisms for managing output stream states. It operates on an opaque serializer type, enabling direct buffer manipulation and efficient data transmission. Functions include writing integers and floats of various bit widths, scheduling raw byte sequences, and tracking flush/drain events. This allows precise control over binary data formatting for network protocols, file formats, and I/O operations.
